				<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/9bc0e08179823ca35b2d8a0a3036d1bd?s=40&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g' srcset='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/9bc0e08179823ca35b2d8a0a3036d1bd?s=80&#038;d=mm&#038;r=g 2x' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />				<cite class="fn">on a mountain</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>			</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
				
			<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="index.html#comment-427673">
				August 23, 2015 at 05:18					</a>
									</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

				<div class="comment-body"><p>I am writing this as a neutral interested outsider from Europe (like all informed sf readers I have followed this year&#8217;s events).</p>
<p>Maybe an elegant way out of the conundrum would be to give each member one negative vote (that they would place in a category of their choice), where it would be declared who certainly should not deserve an award, thus adding a negative tally to the votes. This would not eliminate, but certainly dampen the impact of political voting.</p>
<p>Saying that, in Europe we have known the problem of blatant political voting for decades in the (in)famous &#8220;Concours Eurovision de la Chanson&#8221;. And yet, every year the least awful song actually seems to win. There is a lesson in there somewhere.</p>
</div>

